Dear Shubha,

Here is one way to solve your problem in JUnit 4.5. The key is understanding
that in 4.5 every test is run by a &quot;block&quot; of &quot;statements&quot; (see
http://threeriversi nstitute. org/TwoMoreImple mentationPattern s.htm for more
details). Befores and afters are run by statements high up in the block. The
last statement in the block just invokes the test method. You can modify
this behavior by wrapping this statement in a statement that measures time.
Here&#39;s an overview of the sample code below:
* NanoTimer is a little utility to measure time (at the end we&#39;ll make
sure that timing just the test takes less than half the time of timing the
test including @Before and @After)
* MeasuringInvoker wraps a Statement and times it. You will probably want
to save your timing measurements somewhere for later reporting.
* The MeasuringRunner extends the default BlockJUnit4ClassRun ner by
wrapping the superclass&#39; default invoker with our MeasuringInvoker.

That&#39;s the body of the extension.. What follows is a self-test of the code.
The sample class has a @Before and @After to start and end measuring the
overall time. The test ensures that the time required for just the test
method is less than half of the time required for the whole test including
befores and afters.

I hope this helps.

Regards,

Kent Beck
Three Rivers Institute
public class MeasureTestOnlyTime Test {

static class NanoTimer {
private long start;
private long end;
public void start() { start= System.nanoTime( ); }
public void end() { end= System.nanoTime( ); }
public long duration() { return end - start; }
}

static NanoTimer all= new NanoTimer();
static NanoTimer justTest= new NanoTimer();

static class MeasuringInvoker extends Statement {
private final Statement invoker;

public MeasuringInvoker( Statement invoker) {
this.invoker= invoker;
}

@Override
public void evaluate() throws Throwable {
justTest.start( );
invoker.evaluate( );
justTest.end( );
}
}

public static class MeasuringRunner extends BlockJUnit4ClassRun ner {
public MeasuringRunner( Class&lt; ? &gt; klass) throws InitializationError {
super(klass) ;
}

@Override
protected Statement invoke(FrameworkMet hod method, Object test) {
return new MeasuringInvoker( super.invoke( method, test));
}
}

@RunWith(MeasuringR unner.class)
public static class LongBeforeAndAfter {
@Before public void before() {
all.start();
}
@After public void after() {
all.end();
}
@Test public void test() {
}
}

@Test public void dontMeasureBeforeAn dAfter() {
JUnitCore.runClasse s(LongBeforeAndA fter.class) ;
assertTrue(all. duration( ) &gt; justTest.duration( ) * 2);
}
}

